commentBody:
@Heather Hadlock

I noticed several words in this category. There was 38A BINET for the IQ test. 42D DimWITTED and also 38D [Masters] GURUS, supposed to be wise guys.

We could look also at 6A CHOP! "To have one's chops" means to be skilled and have expertise!

@Roberto

Bazinga.

(But then they could still reproduce.)

@Roberto

Apparently not.

If we do, we apparently vote them right back in again.

@Barry Ancona

16:30 yesterday, a very slow Wednesday for me

12:30 today, a slightly speedy Thursday for me and what would have been a rather slow Wednesday for me

@Henry Su

Ouch!  Hope all is well.  As a physician, I'd hazard to say that completing a NYT XWD while waiting for scan results puts the "F" in "FMRI".  (Meaning your brain is functioning well.). 

Wishing you a speedy recovery!

@Chris 

Maybe I'm misreading your comment, but did you notice that they didn't just "appear *somewhere* in the answer" (emphasis mine)? The location was specified by the answer (opening, center, ending) which made the answer define the clue.

I would say it's on the basic side as a theme and a very fast Thursday, but cute enough cluing.

@Bill

I appreciate the honk!  Thought that might be you.  (Joking, in case you find that to be a strange comment.)

My Sister's Place is great.  We eat there a lot.

@SP

Now, *that* was a Thursday puzzle.

Thank you!

@SP

A Thursday puzzle that makes a solver happy for Thursdays.

I called it up in the Archives and had to re-set the solved puzzle, and it *still* was an total surprise and joy to (re-)solve.

@Matt

But still… kind of a condescending congratulations? I want my Thursdays to be more than a Good Boy. I want a Great Boy. I want a boy that can confound and delight me. 

This was not a bad puzzle. In fact, I thought it was a pretty good puzzle. I just didn’t think it was a Thursday puzzle. (Wag, wag, sniff.)

@Andrzej

Back when I thought I could write I took a seminar with him in New Hampshire.

He was a great teacher, too.

@Andrzej

It's just like the fortune cookie or orange wedge you get with the check at certain Chinese-(American/European) restaurants.

You wouldn't miss it if they didn't bring it but it's a bit of fun all the same.

@Becky

The two-part answer is THE LONG GOODBYE. The other theme answer is the brand DE LONGHI, which is to be parsed as DE (I.e. “the”) LONG HI. 

That’s all.

@Matt
@Steve L
