Again, different species. 
Probably. In the U.S. 'wildcat' is usually the bobcat, Lynx rufus.

@Mean Old Lady

I really liked the trick.  More themers are always nice, but this particular one would be hard to expand.

I'm so very sorry about your friend.  Truly awful.

@SP

You might be right. I'm simply guessing.

Hope you're wrong. Thursday "trickery" has been part of my NYT solving experience since I started maybe 35 years ago. Would be sad to learn that it is being intentionally stifled, in order to please newer solvers and maintain revenue streams.

@The X-Phile

I did the same initially. But MELH just looked too strange. (Was he killed by a Spice Girl? Was MELH even one of them?)

Then I thought of METH, and simply assumed that TOONIE was correct.

@Nancy J.

You are not dreaming, I'm afraid.

You are hallucinating.

@Ryan

Opening, center, ending.

This theme seems rather self-limiting.

@D

Since "late week" generally refers to Friday and Saturday, I can only assume that you're using ESP with respect to those future puzzles.
Your opinion of mid-week puzzles (Wednesday/Thursday) is noted.

@The X-Phile

Play nice, kids. X, you and I both don’t appreciate D’s tone, but you knew what he meant. And it’s not a falsehood to state your opinion. I wish D would expressly say “in my opinion” at the beginning of his posts, so he doesn’t imply we are all stupid for appreciating something he didn’t; but at this point I just mentally insert that at the beginning of all his posts, and suggest you do the same.

Finally, D (in my opinion) there is after all a grain of truth to what you say. But you undercut your argument by hyperbole. “Worthless and inane?” Hardly justifiable. But “Disappointing and uninspiring”? Yeah, I could get behind that, or at least see where you’re coming from.

@Barry Ancona,
Hoyt’s brother Bill, was the coach for Clemson baseball for a long time when I was a kid. I used to shag foul balls and homers during the games, and at the end, they’d give me a single baseball as a reward for “helping out”. 

Once, they even let me be batboy for the first half of a double header. I was fired when I retrieved the bats and took them back to the Clemson dugout, …not only for the Clemson side, but for the visiting team!

